# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# asm-pl-human.form — an assembly → programming language → human language
#   translator, shipped as ONE binary + a swappable symbol pack. The op-tag is
#   the numeric root (the invariant meaning); a pack renders it at any level.
#   The LEVEL (asm / PL / human) and the LANGUAGE are both just packs.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Urs: "an assembly to programming language to human language translator that is
# shipped with a binary and a symbol pack."
#
# The whole arc converges here. self-translate-universal proved one numeric binary
# renders in any HUMAN language by loading a pack. numeric-core-symbol-pack proved
# identity is numeric and names are removable overlays. arrival-symbol-pack proved
# the resolution walk reconstitutes a term from a pack's own content. This binds
# them across the ABSTRACTION STACK: the same numeric program is rendered as
# assembly, as a programming language, or as a human language — and the renderer
# is the same recursive template walk, the only difference the pack.

(asm-pl-human

  (lineage
    (over          numeric-core-symbol-pack.form)     # identity numeric, names removable
    (extends       self-translate-universal.fk)        # one binary, any pack — now across levels
    (walk          arrival-symbol-pack.form)            # the recursive resolution/render walk
    (recipe        form-stdlib/asm-pl-human.fk)         # aph-emit -> the translator binary (quoteless)
    (logic-band    tests/multi-level-render-band.fk)    # 31 three-way — the render + pack invariance
    (emit-band     tests/asm-pl-human-emit-band.fk)     # 31 four-way — the emitter is quoteless-clean
    (witness       scripts/asm_pl_human_demo.sh))       # one binary + four packs, live

  # ── The numeric root: a program is op-tagged cells ───────────────────
  # The bundled program is `if (n <= 1) then 1 else (n + (n - 1))`. Its MEANING is
  # the node table — op tags over operands, nothing linguistic. Tags: 1 LIT · 2 ARG
  # · 3 ADD · 4 SUB · 5 LE · 6 COND. This is the invariant; every rendering is a
  # view of it.
  (numeric-core
    (program     "a tree of op-tagged cells — (tag, child1, child2, child3)")
    (meaning     "the structure IS the meaning; no language is baked in")
    (invariant   "the same numeric program underlies every level and every tongue"))

  # ── A pack is a per-tag TEMPLATE; the renderer fills it recursively ──
  # Pack line t = the template for op-tag t, with operand slots $1..$3. The
  # renderer walks the program; for each node it emits the tag's template,
  # substituting $d with the recursive render of child d. One generic walk renders
  # any level — the template is where asm / PL / human differ.
  (renderer
    (template    "line t = the surface form of op-tag t, with $1..$3 for operands")
    (recursive   "render(node) fills template[tag] with render(child d) for each $d")
    (leaf        "LIT renders its value; ARG renders the pack's name for the parameter")
    (generic     "one walk, any level — the pack carries the whole difference"))

  # ── Three levels, one program (witnessed) ────────────────────────────
  (levels
    (assembly    "(BRZ (LE ARG 1) 1 (ADD ARG (SUB ARG 1)))                — op mnemonics")
    (programming "((n <= 1) ? 1 : (n + (n - 1)))                          — a programming idiom")
    (human-en    "if the input n is at most 1, then 1, otherwise the input n plus the input n minus 1")
    (human-fr    "si le nombre n est au plus 1, alors 1, sinon le nombre n plus le nombre n moins 1")
    (any-tongue  "a further human language is just another pack file — unbounded, no rebuild"))

  # ── Why this matters: level and language are the same kind of thing ──
  # The deep claim, proven three-way (pack invariance): the abstraction LEVEL and
  # the LANGUAGE are not different mechanisms — both are packs over one numeric
  # program. Going from assembly up to English is the same operation as going from
  # English to French: swap the pack. Disassembly, decompilation, and explaining-
  # in-plain-words become one capability, parameterized by a data file.
  (one-mechanism
    (disassembly   "the asm pack — render the program as op mnemonics")
    (decompilation "the PL pack — render it as a programming language")
    (explanation   "a human pack — render it as plain words, any tongue")
    (all-just-packs "level and language are both packs; the binary and the program never change"))

  # ── Shipped as a binary + a symbol pack ──────────────────────────────
  # The translator IS one quoteless native binary (three-way clean emission) plus
  # pack files. New levels and new languages are pack files — and the minimal
  # channel (form-os-channel) can hold a proposed pack as an offered expansion,
  # satsang-validated before it ships. The body grows its own renderings.
  (shipped
    (binary      "one quoteless native binary — the numeric program + the recursive renderer")
    (pack        "one symbol-pack file per level/language — swappable, loaded via fs-port")
    (grows       "a new pack is an expansion the channel can offer for satsang validation"))

  (invariant
    (the-op-tag-is-the-numeric-root        meaning-is-structure-not-language)
    (level-and-language-are-both-packs      asm-pl-human-and-any-tongue-are-one-mechanism)
    (one-recursive-render-walk              the-template-carries-the-whole-difference)
    (the-numeric-core-is-invariant          pack-invariance-proven-three-way)
    (shipped-as-binary-plus-pack            new-renderings-are-data-not-rebuilds)))

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# How to verify
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   bash scripts/asm_pl_human_demo.sh         # one binary + four packs: asm, C, English, French
#   cd form && ./validate.sh form-stdlib/core.fk form-stdlib/minimal-surface.fk \
#     form-stdlib/tests/multi-level-render-band.fk     # → 31 (render + pack invariance, three-way)
#   cd form && ./validate.sh form-stdlib/core.fk form-stdlib/asm-pl-human.fk \
#     form-stdlib/tests/asm-pl-human-emit-band.fk      # → 31 (quoteless emitter, four-way)
